<paragraph blockId="4.[159,1155,1564,1728]" box="[160,276,1564,1590]" pageId="4" pageNumber="177">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,276,1564,1590]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="177">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[159,1155,1564,1728]" lastBlockId="5.[159,1155,142,237]" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="178" pageId="4" pageNumber="177">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zhang, Gates and Campos" authorityYear="2022" box="[160,366,1599,1624]" class="Insecta" family="Eurytomidae" genus="Aximopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="177" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gabrielae">
<emphasis box="[160,366,1599,1624]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="177">Aximopsis gabrielae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from other members of 
<taxonomicName box="[852,957,1599,1624]" class="Insecta" family="Eurytomidae" genus="Aximopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="177" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" sensu="lato">
<emphasis box="[852,957,1599,1624]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="177">Aximopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[962,989,1599,1624]" pageId="4" pageNumber="177" sensu="lato">
<emphasis box="[962,983,1599,1624]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="177">s.l</emphasis>
.
</taxonomicNameLabel>
by the absence of horns on the vertex and mesodorsal pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[732,833,1634,1659]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="3.[160,225,1610,1633]" captionTargetBox="[162,1127,142,1577]" captionTargetId="figure-3@3.[162,1154,142,1578]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figure 2. Aximopsis gabrielae sp. nov. (a) Female lateral habitus. (b) Male lateral habitus. Photos by Miles Zhang." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6530286" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6530286/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="177">Figures 2</figureCitation>
(a–b), 3(a)), 
<emphasis box="[963,1021,1634,1659]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="177">sensu</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Gates MW &amp; Metz MA &amp; Schauff ME" pageId="4" pageNumber="177" pagination="9 - 54" refId="ref4452" refString="Gates MW, Metz MA, Schauff ME. 2006. The circumscription of the generic concept of Aximopsis Ashmead (Hymenoptera: Chalcidoidea: Eurytomidae) with the description of seven new species. Zootaxa. 1273: 9 - 54. doi: 10.11646 / zootaxa. 1273.1.2." type="journal article" year="2006">Gates et al. (2006)</bibRefCitation>
, the clypeus ventrally protruding, the protuberant supraclypeal area forming a bump (
<figureCitation box="[167,268,1703,1728]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="6.[160,226,1575,1598]" captionTargetBox="[163,1152,143,1541]" captionTargetId="figure-3@6.[162,1154,142,1543]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figure 3. Aximopsis gabrielae sp. nov. (a) Head in frontal view, arrow pointing to protuberant supraclypeal area. (b) Female antenna. Photos by Miles Zhang." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6530288" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6530288/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="177">Figures 3</figureCitation>
(a), 4(b)) and the very short, cup-like funiculars in the female. The male has four funiculars very shortly tapering basally and not at all tapering apically, and a two-segmented clava, with a slight division near the tip (
<figureCitation box="[621,711,177,202]" captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="12.[160,225,1577,1600]" captionTargetBox="[162,1153,145,1545]" captionTargetId="figure-16@12.[162,1154,142,1545]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figure 8. Aximopsis gabrielae sp. nov., male.(a) Antenna. (b) Metasoma in lateral view. Photos by Miles Zhang." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6530300" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6530300/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="178">Figure 8</figureCitation>
(a)), while all other known species have strongly tapering F1–F4, giving the appearance of a peduncle for the following segment.
</paragraph>
