<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="178" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="5.[160,1156,558,618]" pageId="5" pageNumber="178">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,245,558,584]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="178">Colour.</emphasis>
Black except for the following: flagellomeres, tegula, wing veins brown; scape, pedicel, apices of femora, tibiae, tarsi, ovipositor sheaths testaceous (
<figureCitation box="[938,1031,593,618]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="3.[160,225,1610,1633]" captionTargetBox="[162,1127,142,1577]" captionTargetId="figure-3@3.[162,1154,142,1578]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figure 2. Aximopsis gabrielae sp. nov. (a) Female lateral habitus. (b) Male lateral habitus. Photos by Miles Zhang." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6530286" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6530286/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="178">Figure 2</figureCitation>
(a)).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[160,1156,662,1104]" pageId="5" pageNumber="178">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,229,662,688]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="178">Head.</emphasis>
Rectangular and 1.25× as wide as long in dorsal view, with umbilicate sculpture and bearing filiform, adpressed and sparse setae, those on lower face longer and directed downwards, the others shorter and directed upwards. Lower face strigose, the carinulae converging towards edge of oral fossa and extending above to antennal toruli, clypeus distinctly protruding, its surface forming a bump, mandible weakly tridentate (
<figureCitation box="[1024,1114,801,826]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="6.[160,226,1575,1598]" captionTargetBox="[163,1152,143,1541]" captionTargetId="figure-3@6.[162,1154,142,1543]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figure 3. Aximopsis gabrielae sp. nov. (a) Head in frontal view, arrow pointing to protuberant supraclypeal area. (b) Female antenna. Photos by Miles Zhang." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6530288" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6530288/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="178">Figure 3</figureCitation>
(a)). Malar sulcus absent, malar space 0.62× eye height. Genal carina present, malar sulcus forming a small asetose, imbricate band below eyes. Toruli positioned above lower ocular line, diameter of torulus 1.5× that of the intertorular space. Scrobal depression carinate laterally, with parallel edges, ventromedially carinate. Vertex imbricate, POL:OOL:LOL ratio 2.5:1.4:1. Head posteriorly with postgenal lamina, postgenal groove straight, fading about at level with upper edge of hypostomal carina, and slightly converging ventrally, ending far from genal carina. Subforaminal bridge transversely strigulose and with broad median strip of ornamentation. Posterior tentorial sulci present and deep (
<figureCitation box="[908,1001,1079,1104]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="7.[160,225,1577,1600]" captionTargetBox="[162,1154,142,1545]" captionTargetId="figure-3@7.[162,1154,142,1545]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figure 4. Aximopsis gabrielae sp. nov. (a) Head in posterior view. (b) Female, anterolateral view; inset: procoxa in anterior view, arrow pointing to the oblique groove. Photos by Miles Zhang." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6530290" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6530290/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="178">Figure 4</figureCitation>
(a)).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[160,1156,1147,1277]" pageId="5" pageNumber="178">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,268,1147,1173]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="178">Antenna.</emphasis>
Ratio of scape (minus radicle):pedicel:anellus:F1:F2:F3:F4:F5:club 12:4:1:4.2:4:4: 3.8:3:8.8; pedicel chalice-shaped; funiculars very short with F2–F4 transverse and cupuliform; funiculars thus bearing a single row of longitudinal sensilla and two whorls of setae, shorter than relevant segment; clava clearly two-segmented (
<figureCitation box="[852,945,1252,1277]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="6.[160,226,1575,1598]" captionTargetBox="[163,1152,143,1541]" captionTargetId="figure-3@6.[162,1154,142,1543]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figure 3. Aximopsis gabrielae sp. nov. (a) Head in frontal view, arrow pointing to protuberant supraclypeal area. (b) Female antenna. Photos by Miles Zhang." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6530288" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6530288/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="178">Figure 3</figureCitation>
(b)).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[160,1155,1321,1416]" pageId="5" pageNumber="178">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,285,1321,1347]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="178">Fore wing.</emphasis>
Ratio of marginal:postmarginal:stigmal veins 1.8:1.2:1. Costal and basal cells and speculum bare except for basal and cubital folds with a line of setae, short setation on the distal parts of the wing (
<figureCitation box="[480,573,1391,1416]" captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="10.[160,225,1251,1274]" captionTargetBox="[162,1154,142,1172]" captionTargetId="figure-118@10.[162,1154,142,1219]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figure 6. Aximopsis gabrielae sp. nov., female.(a) Fore wing. (b) Dorsal habitus. Photos by Miles Zhang." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6530294" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6530294/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="178">Figure 6</figureCitation>
(a)).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="181" pageId="5" pageNumber="178" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[160,1156,1460,1728]" lastBlockId="8.[160,1156,142,237]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="181" pageId="5" pageNumber="178">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,294,1460,1486]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="178">
<taxonomicName box="[160,289,1460,1486]" class="Crustacea (awaiting allocation)" family="Crustacea (awaiting allocation)" genus="Mesosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Crustacea (awaiting allocation)" pageId="5" pageNumber="178" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Mesosoma</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[309,427,1461,1486]" class="Crustacea (awaiting allocation)" family="Crustacea (awaiting allocation)" genus="Mesosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Crustacea (awaiting allocation)" pageId="5" pageNumber="178" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Mesosoma</taxonomicName>
1.33× as long as broad; pro- and mesonotum umbilicate, notauli complete, shallow (
<figureCitation box="[376,469,1495,1520]" captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="10.[160,225,1251,1274]" captionTargetBox="[162,1154,142,1172]" captionTargetId="figure-118@10.[162,1154,142,1219]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figure 6. Aximopsis gabrielae sp. nov., female.(a) Fore wing. (b) Dorsal habitus. Photos by Miles Zhang." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6530294" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6530294/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="178">Figure 6</figureCitation>
(b)); lateral prepectus triangular, smooth, sublateral prepectus with deep pit; ventral surface of prepectus with median tooth (
<figureCitation box="[930,1029,1530,1555]" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="9.[160,225,1577,1600]" captionTargetBox="[163,1154,142,1545]" captionTargetId="figure-3@9.[162,1154,142,1545]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Figure 5. Aximopsis gabrielae sp. nov. (a) Mesosoma in lateral view. (b) Mesosoma in lateroventral view, arrow pointing to median tooth on prepectus. Photos by Miles Zhang." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6530292" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6530292/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="178">Figure 5</figureCitation>
(b), arrow). Adscrobal area with three long and erect setae. Mesopleuron strigose, epicnemium flat, entirely carinately delimited (
<figureCitation box="[498,593,1599,1624]" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="9.[160,225,1577,1600]" captionTargetBox="[163,1154,142,1545]" captionTargetId="figure-3@9.[162,1154,142,1545]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Figure 5. Aximopsis gabrielae sp. nov. (a) Mesosoma in lateral view. (b) Mesosoma in lateroventral view, arrow pointing to median tooth on prepectus. Photos by Miles Zhang." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6530292" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6530292/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="178">Figure 5</figureCitation>
(a)), anterior projection of ventral shelf elevated, narrowly projecting anteriorly (
<figureCitation box="[512,607,1634,1659]" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="9.[160,225,1577,1600]" captionTargetBox="[163,1154,142,1545]" captionTargetId="figure-3@9.[162,1154,142,1545]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Figure 5. Aximopsis gabrielae sp. nov. (a) Mesosoma in lateral view. (b) Mesosoma in lateroventral view, arrow pointing to median tooth on prepectus. Photos by Miles Zhang." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6530292" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6530292/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="178">Figure 5</figureCitation>
(b)). Ventral part of the femoral depression with a large areola (
<figureCitation box="[329,422,1669,1694]" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="9.[160,225,1577,1600]" captionTargetBox="[163,1154,142,1545]" captionTargetId="figure-3@9.[162,1154,142,1545]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Figure 5. Aximopsis gabrielae sp. nov. (a) Mesosoma in lateral view. (b) Mesosoma in lateroventral view, arrow pointing to median tooth on prepectus. Photos by Miles Zhang." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6530292" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6530292/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="178">Figure 5</figureCitation>
(b)). Metepimeron regularly umbilicate and bearing long, hair-like setae. Postscutellum with inverted V-like raised strip forming a very obtuse angle. Propodeum flattened medially, the relevant surface carinately delimited laterally, reticulate anteriorly and transversely strigulose laterally, followed by subquadrate adpetiolar areola; propodeum coarsely umbilicate laterally and bearing filiform, erect setae (
<figureCitation box="[982,1074,212,237]" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="11.[160,225,1577,1600]" captionTargetBox="[163,1154,143,1545]" captionTargetId="figure-18@11.[162,1154,142,1545]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Figure 7. Aximopsis gabrielae sp. nov., female. (a) Metasoma in lateral view. (b) Propodeum in dorsal view. Photos by Miles Zhang." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6530296" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6530296/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="181">Figure 7</figureCitation>
(b)).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6530288" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6530288" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6530288/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="179" startId="6.[160,226,1575,1598]" targetBox="[163,1152,143,1541]" targetPageId="6">
<paragraph blockId="6.[160,1155,1575,1627]" pageId="6" pageNumber="179">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,256,1575,1598]" pageId="6" pageNumber="179">Figure 3.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Campos-Moreno &amp; Gates &amp; Zhang &amp; Pérez-Lachaud &amp; Dyer &amp; Whitfield &amp; Pozo, 2022" authorityName="Campos-Moreno &amp; Gates &amp; Zhang &amp; Pérez-Lachaud &amp; Dyer &amp; Whitfield &amp; Pozo" authorityYear="2022" box="[267,465,1575,1598]" class="Insecta" family="Eurytomidae" genus="Aximopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gabrielae" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[267,465,1575,1598]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="179">Aximopsis gabrielae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[476,559,1575,1598]" pageId="6" pageNumber="179" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
(a) Head in frontal view, arrow pointing to protuberant supraclypeal area. (b) Female antenna. Photos by Miles Zhang.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6530290" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6530290" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6530290/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="180" startId="7.[160,225,1577,1600]" targetBox="[162,1154,142,1545]" targetPageId="7">
<paragraph blockId="7.[160,1157,1577,1629]" pageId="7" pageNumber="180">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,250,1577,1600]" pageId="7" pageNumber="180">Figure 4.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Campos-Moreno &amp; Gates &amp; Zhang &amp; Pérez-Lachaud &amp; Dyer &amp; Whitfield &amp; Pozo, 2022" authorityName="Campos-Moreno &amp; Gates &amp; Zhang &amp; Pérez-Lachaud &amp; Dyer &amp; Whitfield &amp; Pozo" authorityYear="2022" box="[256,445,1577,1600]" class="Insecta" family="Eurytomidae" genus="Aximopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="180" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gabrielae" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[256,445,1577,1600]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="180">Aximopsis gabrielae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[452,529,1577,1600]" pageId="7" pageNumber="180" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
(a) Head in posterior view. (b) Female, anterolateral view; inset: procoxa in anterior view, arrow pointing to the oblique groove. Photos by Miles Zhang.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="181" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="8.[160,1155,280,375]" pageId="8" pageNumber="181">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,209,280,306]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="181">Leg.</emphasis>
Oblique carina on procoxa forming a shelf for reception of lower head (
<figureCitation box="[1028,1121,281,306]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="7.[160,225,1577,1600]" captionTargetBox="[162,1154,142,1545]" captionTargetId="figure-3@7.[162,1154,142,1545]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figure 4. Aximopsis gabrielae sp. nov. (a) Head in posterior view. (b) Female, anterolateral view; inset: procoxa in anterior view, arrow pointing to the oblique groove. Photos by Miles Zhang." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6530290" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6530290/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="181">Figure 4</figureCitation>
(b), arrow), imbricate. Mesocoxa without lamella; metacoxa bare dorsally, metatibia with a row of adpressed setae, subequal to the width of the metatibia.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[159,1156,419,583]" pageId="8" pageNumber="181">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,292,419,445]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="181">Metasoma.</emphasis>
Petiole longer than metacoxa, cylindrical, rugose to alveolate, 0.4× as long as gaster in lateral view; dorsally with median carina leading to anterior teeth above the ‘canopener’ shaped articular area; no ventral transverse carina delimiting petiole from petiolar part of St1. Gaster elliptical in lateral view, narrowly tapering posteriorly (
<figureCitation box="[935,1021,524,549]" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="11.[160,225,1577,1600]" captionTargetBox="[163,1154,143,1545]" captionTargetId="figure-18@11.[162,1154,142,1545]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Figure 7. Aximopsis gabrielae sp. nov., female. (a) Metasoma in lateral view. (b) Propodeum in dorsal view. Photos by Miles Zhang." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6530296" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6530296/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="181">Figure 7</figureCitation>
(a)), smooth, setose from Gt4. Gt4 much longer than other tergites, emarginate posteriorly in dorsal view.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[159,1155,627,861]" pageId="8" pageNumber="181">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,225,627,653]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="181">Male.</emphasis>
Length 
<quantity box="[324,408,628,653]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.2" pageId="8" pageNumber="181" unit="mm" value="2.2">2.2 mm</quantity>
. Colour largely similar to females, except antennae wholly black, and tibiae dark brown; sculpture as described for females (
<figureCitation box="[795,891,662,687]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="3.[160,225,1610,1633]" captionTargetBox="[162,1127,142,1577]" captionTargetId="figure-3@3.[162,1154,142,1578]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figure 2. Aximopsis gabrielae sp. nov. (a) Female lateral habitus. (b) Male lateral habitus. Photos by Miles Zhang." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6530286" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6530286/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="181">Figure 2</figureCitation>
(b)). Antenna with four funiculars longer than wide, cupuliform, funiculars with single row of longitudinal sensilla and two or more rows of filiform, erect setae longer than their bearing segment. Clava twosegmented, tip of clava tapering (
<figureCitation box="[525,613,767,792]" captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="12.[160,225,1577,1600]" captionTargetBox="[162,1153,145,1545]" captionTargetId="figure-16@12.[162,1154,142,1545]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figure 8. Aximopsis gabrielae sp. nov., male.(a) Antenna. (b) Metasoma in lateral view. Photos by Miles Zhang." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6530300" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6530300/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="181">Figure 8</figureCitation>
(a)). Gastral petiole in lateral view 0.65× as long as metasoma, cylindrical, weakly reticulate to smooth. Metasoma triangular in shape (
<figureCitation box="[1065,1155,801,826]" captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="12.[160,225,1577,1600]" captionTargetBox="[162,1153,145,1545]" captionTargetId="figure-16@12.[162,1154,142,1545]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figure 8. Aximopsis gabrielae sp. nov., male.(a) Antenna. (b) Metasoma in lateral view. Photos by Miles Zhang." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6530300" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6530300/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="181">Figure 8</figureCitation>
(b)).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[160,1105,904,930]" box="[160,1105,904,930]" pageId="8" pageNumber="181">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,277,904,930]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="181">Variation.</emphasis>
Female body length ranges from 
<quantity box="[670,829,905,930]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.35" metricValueMax="2.5" metricValueMin="2.2" pageId="8" pageNumber="181" unit="mm" value="2.35" valueMax="2.5" valueMin="2.2">2.2 to 2.5 mm</quantity>
, male from 
<quantity box="[962,1102,905,930]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.15" metricValueMax="2.3" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="181" unit="mm" value="2.15" valueMax="2.3" valueMin="2.0">2 to 2.3 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="181" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="8.[160,1157,974,1104]" pageId="8" pageNumber="181">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,258,974,1000]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="181">Biology.</emphasis>
A gregarious larval-pupal endoparasitoid of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Stoll" baseAuthorityYear="1782" box="[807,990,975,1000]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Quadrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="181" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cerialis">
<emphasis box="[807,990,975,1000]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="181">Quadrus cerialis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[1008,1152,975,1000]" class="Insecta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="181" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Lepidoptera</taxonomicName>
: 
<taxonomicName box="[160,294,1009,1034]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="181" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Hesperiidae</taxonomicName>
) feeding on 
<taxonomicName box="[442,602,1009,1034]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Piperaceae" genus="Piper" kingdom="Plantae" order="Piperales" pageId="8" pageNumber="181" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="amalago">
<emphasis box="[442,602,1009,1034]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="181">Piper amalago</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[618,746,1009,1034]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Piperaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Piperales" pageId="8" pageNumber="181" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Piperaceae</taxonomicName>
). Caterpillars of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Stoll" baseAuthorityYear="1782" box="[930,1036,1009,1034]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Quadrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="181" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cerialis">
<emphasis box="[930,1036,1009,1034]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="181">Q. cerialis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are abundant in August (unpublished data), the month when 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Campos-Moreno &amp; Gates &amp; Zhang &amp; Pérez-Lachaud &amp; Dyer &amp; Whitfield &amp; Pozo" authorityYear="2022" box="[768,898,1044,1069]" class="Insecta" family="Eurytomidae" genus="Aximopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="181" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gabrielae">
<emphasis box="[768,898,1044,1069]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="181">A. gabrielae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
parasitised one of the caterpillars collected.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="181" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="8.[160,1156,1147,1277]" box="[160,300,1147,1173]" pageId="8" pageNumber="181">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,300,1147,1173]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="181">Distribution</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[160,1156,1147,1277]" pageId="8" pageNumber="181">
Southern 
<collectingRegion box="[270,353,1183,1208]" country="Mexico" name="Mexico" pageId="8" pageNumber="181">Mexico</collectingRegion>
, in the 
<collectingRegion box="[435,525,1183,1208]" country="Mexico" name="Yucatan" pageId="8" pageNumber="181">Yucatan</collectingRegion>
Peninsula, in a forest reserve of semi-evergreen tropical forest. This species is probably widespread through the Neotropical Region, where 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Stoll" baseAuthorityYear="1782" box="[160,265,1252,1277]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Quadrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="181" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cerialis">
<emphasis box="[160,265,1252,1277]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="181">Q. cerialis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[323,446,1252,1277]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Piperaceae" genus="Piper" kingdom="Plantae" order="Piperales" pageId="8" pageNumber="181" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="amalago">
<emphasis box="[323,446,1252,1277]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="181">P. amalago</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are distributed.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="181" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="8.[160,1156,1321,1416]" box="[160,285,1321,1347]" pageId="8" pageNumber="181">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,285,1321,1347]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="181">Etymology</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[160,1156,1321,1416]" pageId="8" pageNumber="181">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Campos-Moreno &amp; Gates &amp; Zhang &amp; Pérez-Lachaud &amp; Dyer &amp; Whitfield &amp; Pozo" authorityYear="2022" box="[160,369,1356,1381]" class="Insecta" family="Eurytomidae" genus="Aximopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="181" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gabrielae">
<emphasis box="[160,369,1356,1381]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="181">Aximopsis gabrielae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is named in honour of Gabriela Pérez-Lachaud, who has dedicated most of her life to the study of the ecology and behaviour of parasitoids in south-eastern 
<collectingCountry box="[1071,1152,1391,1416]" name="Mexico" pageId="8" pageNumber="181">Mexico</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
